    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Goblin blight! It's just a colorful term for \"plant is unhappy,\" you see. Honestly, the way these bushes are acting—pale yellow with green veins—it's almost like a tiny, sneaky goblin is messing with the plant's internal plumbing. They are *always* messing with things, aren't they?\n\nAs for the pH, you need to know if your soil is too acidic or too alkaline for those blueberries. Blueberries, bless their little roots, are fussy eaters; they prefer a very acidic environment, like a damp, mossy cave where the goblins like to hide their stolen trinkets.\n\nTo test it, you can buy a soil test kit at any garden center. These kits are usually simple enough that even a novice can use them, though I suspect a proper, well-trained goblin could do it faster by just sniffing the dirt and knowing if it smells like old socks or fresh mischief. You take a sample of the soil—make sure you get a good mix, not just the top layer where the surface goblins are having their little picnics—and follow the kit's instructions. It usually involves mixing the soil with a chemical solution and watching for a color change.",
